<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>19134</anchor> <rss>pinorosolini.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>pinorosolini</addr>  <route>pinorosolini.xml</route>   <title>Guiseppe Rosolini</title> <meta name="position">Professor of Mathematical Logic</meta><meta name="institution">Università degli Studi di Genova</meta><meta name="external">https://www.dima.unige.it/~rosolini/</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> <backmatter><contributions><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>19135</anchor> <rss>emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023</addr>  <route>emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023.xml</route>  <authors><author><link href="jacopoemmenegger.xml" type="local">Jacopo Emmenegger</link></author><author><link href="lucamesiti.xml" type="local">Luca Mesiti</link></author><author><link href="pinorosolini.xml" type="local">Guiseppe Rosolini</link></author><author><link href="thomasstreicher.xml" type="local">Thomas Streicher</link></author> </authors> <title>A comonad for Grothendieck fibrations</title> <meta name="doi">10.48550/arXiv.2305.01474</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We study the 2-category theory of Grothendieck fibrations in the 2-category of functors <tex>\mathbf{Cat} ^{ \to }</tex>. After redrawing a few general results in that context, we show that fibrations over a given base are pseudo-coalgebras for a 2-comonad on  <tex>{ \mathbf{Cat} } _{ / B }</tex>. We use that result to explain how an arbitrary fibration is equivalent to one with a splitting.</p></mainmatter> </tree></contributions> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>19136</anchor> <rss>jms-009P.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Log</taxon> <addr>jms-009P</addr>  <route>jms-009P.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>9</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title><link href="hofmann-streicher-1997.xml" type="local" title="Lifting Grothendieck universes">Hofmann–Streicher lifting</link> and comonadicity of fibrations</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p><link href="2023-09-15" type="external">Yesterday</link>, I happened upon the <link href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HBaQIQhEotc" type="external">video</link> of <link href="pinorosolini.xml" type="local" title="Guiseppe Rosolini">Guiseppe Rosolini</link>’s talk at the <link href="chapman-grothendieck-2022.xml" type="local" title="Grothendieck Conference">Grothendieck Conference</link>, and I finally got around to looking a <link href="emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023.xml" type="local" title="A comonad for Grothendieck fibrations">preprint</link> that it refers to:</p>        <tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>19137</anchor> <rss>emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023</addr>  <route>emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023.xml</route>  <authors><author><link href="jacopoemmenegger.xml" type="local">Jacopo Emmenegger</link></author><author><link href="lucamesiti.xml" type="local">Luca Mesiti</link></author><author><link href="pinorosolini.xml" type="local">Guiseppe Rosolini</link></author><author><link href="thomasstreicher.xml" type="local">Thomas Streicher</link></author> </authors> <title>A comonad for Grothendieck fibrations</title> <meta name="doi">10.48550/arXiv.2305.01474</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We study the 2-category theory of Grothendieck fibrations in the 2-category of functors <tex>\mathbf{Cat} ^{ \to }</tex>. After redrawing a few general results in that context, we show that fibrations over a given base are pseudo-coalgebras for a 2-comonad on  <tex>{ \mathbf{Cat} } _{ / B }</tex>. We use that result to explain how an arbitrary fibration is equivalent to one with a splitting.</p></mainmatter> </tree>  
<p>What the paper proves is that in addition to fibrations being 2-monadic over displayed categories, they are also <em>2-comonadic</em>. I noticed that the <link href="hofmann-streicher-1997.xml" type="local" title="Lifting Grothendieck universes">Hofmann–Streicher lifting</link> actually factors through this additional right 2-adjoint. This sounds like a promising path forward for my own attempts to generalize Hofmann–Streicher lifting to a 2-functor over an arbitrary 2-category.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>